TY  - JOUR
T1  - Disclosure Disconnects: Antecedents and Consequences of Disclosing Invisible Stigmas across Life Domains
AU  - Ragins, Belle Rose
Y1  - 2008/01/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2008.27752724
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2008.27752724
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 194
EP  - 215
VL  - 33
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article broadens our perspective of stigma by examining the process of disclosing an invisible stigmatized identity in work and nonwork domains. I present a model that examines the effects of individual and environmental factors on disclosure decisions across life domains. Individuals may disclose their stigma to varying degrees across life domains, and this inconsistency leads to disclosure disconnects. I examine psychological states and outcomes associated with disclosure disconnects and offer directions for future research.
AB  - This article broadens our perspective of stigma by examining the process of disclosing an invisible stigmatized identity in work and nonwork domains. I present a model that examines the effects of individual and environmental factors on disclosure decisions across life domains. Individuals may disclose their stigma to varying degrees across life domains, and this inconsistency leads to disclosure disconnects. I examine psychological states and outcomes associated with disclosure disconnects and offer directions for future research.
